Sulphur in air streams can significantly affect the performance and durability of SOFCs [191, 215, 216]. For example, Wang et al. [217] studied the mechanism and kinetics of sulphur deposition on LSM electrodes at 700 °C and 800 °C in 1 ppm and 10 ppm SO2 and reported that the deposition of SO2 was likely controlled by the nucleation reaction between surface-segregated SrO and SO2 to form SrSO4 on LSM electrode surfaces. Here, segregated SrO species act as both the nucleation agent and the reactant and the formation of SrSO4 in turn can promote Sr segregation, leading to LSM Sr deficiency and driving the chemical reaction to the LSM/YSZ interface. High oxygen activities and SrO segregation can also lead to the formation of Sr/La zirconate at electrode/electrolyte interfaces.9SO2+SrO→SrSO4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
