				\begin{document}$${\text{SO}}_{2} + {\text{SrO}} \to {\text{SrSO}}_{4}$$\end{document}

Compared with LSM, cobaltite oxygen electrodes such as LSC, Sm0.5Sr0.5CoO3 (SSC) and LSCF have much higher tendencies to react with SO2. For example, Schuler et al. [58, 219] exposed a double-layer oxygen electrode consisting of a LSM–YSZ inner layer and an LSC outer layer to ~ 12 ppb SO2 and reported that after operation at 800 °C for 1900 h, SrSO4 preferentially deposited onto the LSC layer, in which the formation of more SrSO4 on the cobaltite electrodes as compared with that on LSM electrodes was believed to be due to the higher activity of SrO in cobaltite electrodes [58, 190, 191]. Here, the reaction between SO2 and LSC is favourable under oxygen-rich atmospheres and can be described by:106La0.5Sr0.5CoO3+3SO2+12O2→3SrSO4+Co3O4+3LaCoO3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
